<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="527" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,1221]" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1159,1185]" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[847,878,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">
bi 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[869,878,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">-</emphasis>
</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[931,1068,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="527">triangulatus</emphasis>
, referring to the shape of the two posterior lobes of the juxta.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
